<br>
The new PoP raid feature is extremely nice.  Basically, it allows up to 72 people (I think - never hit the limit) to all join a raid.  XP from mobs is divided among everyone in the raid (that can get xp from the mob).  The raid leader has control over everything through the window.  Here's how it works:<br>
<br>
Anyone can open the raid window at any time.  To do this type /raidwindow or hold down alt and press &quot;r&quot;  (alt-r).  This brings up the raid window.  The window shows who is in each group, and their class and level.  It also tells you at the bottom how many are in the raid and what the average level is.<br>
<br>
At the start, nobody will be in the raid.  Target someone and click the invite button, or type /raidinvite.  The person then needs to type /raidaccept.  This brings the raid leader and the person in as GROUP LEADERS.  If more groups are needed, repeat the process until you have enough group leaders.  At this time, you can talk in the raid channel by using /rsay.<br>
<br>
There will be no groups at this point, everyone will be listed at the bottom.  Now, the group leaders invite people into their groups just as they would if they were not in a raid.  If a group leader invites someone in, they become a raid group, and their names get moved to one of the groups in the main part of the raid window.  All regular members need to do to get into the raid is click the follow button.<br>
<br>
Once all the groups are full, and everyone is talking merrily in the /rsay channel, the raid begins.  A mob is killed and everyone gets xp.  No complaining that they aren't in the main group.  But wait - only the raid leader can loot.<br>
<br>
The raid leader has to define looters.  The default is leader only.  Click the options button in the raid window.  You'll see a drop down menu that says Leader Only.  You can change this to Raid Leader and Group Leaders or Leader Selected.  There is no choice for &quot;ALL&quot; which is annoying.  If you choose Raid Leader and Group Leaders, only those people will be allowed to loot, until the mob &quot;opens up&quot; for all.  However, if you chose leader selected, you have more work to do.  Close the Options Window and go back to the main Raid Window.  Highlight each member whom you want to make a looter.  Highlight them and click Add Looter.  They are now added to the looter list.  Repeat until all your looters are added.  NOTE:  You can't get everyone on the list - the maximum number is somewhere around 10 or so, our average raid has 3 or 4 people that can't loot - again, annoying.<br>
<br>
To remove loot monkeys from the loot list, highlight their name and click Remove Looter.  You can disband people from the raid in the same manner by clicking the disband button.<br>
<br>
Now, let's say some people have to leave and 2 people from group 3 leave and 4 people from group 4 leave.  One of the members drops group 4 and joins group 3 no problem.  But the leader of group 4 cannot be invited into group 3 because he is a group leader.  He must leave the raid first, to lose his group leader status.  The raid leader may disband him, or group 4 leader opens the raid window and clicks Disband.  Then he may be invited into group 3 normally, and the raid continues.<br>
<br>
That's basically it, there are other features, but they aren't necessary.  It's pretty self-explanitory once you get into it.<br>
<br>
Summary of raid commands:<br>
<br>
/raidwindow - toggles the raid window <br>
/makeraidleader [name]- reassigns raid leadership - Optional argument, name of raid member to be new leader, or you can just target them. If you type a person's name, that name is used instead of your current raid window target. <br>
/raidinvite - invites the current target to the raid <br>
/raidaccept - accepts an invitation to a raid <br>
/raiddecline - declines an invitation to a raid. <br>
/raidremove - removed the current raid target from the raid <br>
/setloottype # - sets the raid loot type - Takes one number argument: 1, 2, 3. <br>
/addraidlooter - adds a raid member as an early looter to all future corpses - Target a raid member in raid window. <br>
/removeraidlooter - removes a raid member as a possible looter from all future corpses - Target a raid member in raid window. <br>
/rsay - Sends a message to all members of the raid <br>
